    "subject": {
      "id": "RA_EN_002"
    },
    "input": "A 58-year-old Japanese man experienced blurred vision one week after receiving the second dose of the COVID-19 mRNA vaccine (BNT162b2, Pfizer, Tokyo, Japan) in 2021. Three months later, he began to experience headache, nausea, and vertigo. An MRI scan of his head showed no abnormalities. Due to worsening blurred vision and the onset of tinnitus, he consulted an ophthalmologist and was found to have iritis and uveitis. He reported leukoderma on his head and was referred to our hospital nine months after his second vaccination. Upon examination, he had depigmentation on his bilateral forehead and forearm in multiple coalescing patches, as well as annular erythema on his bilateral upper arms. His medical history included pompholyx and atopic dermatitis. Laboratory tests revealed elevated serum levels of immunoglobulin E (IgE) at 1,561 IU/mL and thymus and activation-regulated chemokine (TARC) at 1,050 pg/mL. Serum thyroid-stimulating hormone, free T3, and free T4 levels were within normal limits. Autoantibodies, including antinuclear antibody, anti-SS-A, and anti-SS-B antibody, were negative.",
    "target": "Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada disease",
